scenario:
The shown call itself does not invoke memcmp and therefore does not by itself violate Rule 21.14. A violation would occur if the callback OS_ObjectNameMatch compared null-terminated strings using memcmp, for example:

static bool OS_ObjectNameMatch(void *arg, const OS_object_internal_t *obj)
{
    const char *name = (const char *)arg;
    /* VIOLATION: using memcmp to compare null-terminated C strings */
    return (memcmp(name, obj->name, OS_MAX_API_NAME) == 0);
}

This implementation would violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14. The safe alternatives are to use strcmp/strncmp or otherwise compare using explicit known lengths for non-null-terminated buffers.
